   <refnamediv>
       <refname>trimr</refname>
               <refpurpose>strip a matrix </refpurpose>
   </refnamediv>
 
        <refsynopsisdiv>
               <title>CALLING SEQUENCE</title>
               <synopsis>[z]=trimr(x,n1,n2)</synopsis>
        </refsynopsisdiv>
 
        <refsection>
           <title>PARAMETERS</title>
           <variablelist>
           <varlistentry>
 
           <term>Input</term>
 
<listitem><para>*  <term> x </term> =    input matrix (or vector) (n x k)</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>*  <term> n1 </term> =    first n1 rows to strip</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>*  <term> n2 </term> =    last n2 rows to strip</para></listitem>
 
 
 
<listitem><para>&#160;</para></listitem>
 
           </varlistentry>
 
          <varlistentry>
 
          <term>Output</term>
<listitem><para>*  <term> z </term> =    x(n1+1:n-n2,:) </para></listitem>
 
 
          </varlistentry>
          </variablelist>
        </refsection>
 
        <refsection>
               <title>DESCRIPTION</title>
Returns a matrix (or vector) x stripped of the specified rows. Modelled after Gauss trimr function. 

        </refsection>
 
        <refsection>
               <title>EXAMPLE</title>
              <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
 trimr([1:10]',2,3)// returns:
//!   3. !//!   4. !//!   5. !//!   6. !//!   7. !
               ]]></programlisting>
        </refsection>
 
        <refsection>
               <title>AUTHOR</title>
